05914nam a22009255i 9780812207521DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)883825063  a97808122075217 a10.9783/97808122075212doi  a(DE-B1597)449647  a(OCoLC)830022824  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBX2612.A79bA76 2013 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a271/.10493462231 aArnold, Ellen F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNegotiating the Landscape :bEnvironment and Monastic Identity in the Medieval Ardennes /cEllen F. Arnold. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Middle Ages Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Approaching the Medieval Landscape -- tChapter 1. Religious Roots -- tChapter 2. Controlling the Domesticated Landscape -- tChapter 3. Fighting over Forests -- tChapter 4. Creating Conflict -- tChapter 5. The Religious Landscape and Monastic Identity -- tEpilogue. The Passio Agilolfi Revisited -- tTimeline -- tHandlist of Sources -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNegotiating the Landscape explores the question of how medieval religious identities were shaped and modified by interaction with the natural environment. Focusing on the Benedictine monastic community of Stavelot-Malmedy in the Ardennes, Ellen F. Arnold draws upon a rich archive of charters, property and tax records, correspondence, miracle collections, and saints' lives from the seventh to the mid-twelfth century to explore the contexts in which the monks' intense engagement with the natural world was generated and refined.Arnold argues for a broad cultural approach to medieval environmental history and a consideration of a medieval environmental imagination through which people perceived the nonhuman world and their own relation to it. Concerned to reassert medieval Christianity's vitality and variety, Arnold also seeks to oppose the historically influential view that the natural world was regarded in the premodern period as provided by God solely for human use and exploitation. The book argues that, rather than possessing a single unifying vision of nature, the monks drew on their ideas and experience to create and then manipulate a complex understanding of their environment. Viewing nature as both wild and domestic, they simultaneously acted out several roles, as stewards of the land and as economic agents exploiting natural resources. They saw the natural world of the Ardennes as a type of wilderness, a pastoral haven, and a source of human salvation, and actively incorporated these differing views of nature into their own attempts to build their community, understand and establish their religious identity, and relate to others who shared their landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBenedictine monasteriesxBelgiumxStavelotxHistoryxTo 1500. 0aBenedictine monasterieszBelgiumzStavelotxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aHISTORYxMedieval. 0aHuman ecologyxReligious aspectsxCatholic ChurchxHistoryxTo 1500. 0aHuman ecologyxReligious aspectsxCatholic ChurchxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aHuman ecologyxReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 0aHuman ecologyzArdennesxHistoryxTo 1500. 0aHuman ecologyzArdennesxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aLandscapesxReligious aspectsxHistoryxTo 1500. 0aLandscapesxReligious aspectsxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aLandscapesxReligious aspects. 0aLandscapeszArdennesxHistoryxTo 1500. 0aLandscapeszArdennesxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aReligious Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aHistory.  aMed